INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'ea19fed9-1fc2-4951-bc3b-b6dc212211b4',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$WebSockets vs gRPC Streaming — When to Drop the Raw Duplex Channel$escape$,
  $escape$WebSocket connections give you a raw duplex channel — you own message framing, schema versioning, and multiplexing. gRPC bidirectional streaming (`stream Req returns (stream Res)`) gives you the same persistent-connection semantics over HTTP/2 but with protobuf contracts enforced at compile time, plus built-in flow control and connection multiplexing (multiple logical streams over one TCP connection).

gRPC defines four call types: unary, server streaming, client streaming, and bidirectional. Map these to your WebSocket patterns before migrating. The common WS pattern — client sends one message, server pushes N updates — maps directly to server streaming (`returns (stream T)`). True back-and-forth maps to bidirectional streaming, the closest analogue to a raw WebSocket.

Where WebSockets still win: browser-initiated bidirectional streams. gRPC-Web doesn't support client or bidirectional streaming in the browser — you'll still need WebSockets or SSE there. But in your service-to-service layer, gRPC replaces WebSockets cleanly: protobuf schemas eliminate the ad-hoc JSON envelopes you're likely maintaining, and HTTP/2 multiplexing cuts per-stream connection overhead significantly.$escape$,
  $escape$// WS equivalent: conn.ReadMessage() in a loop, but now schema-enforced
stream, err := client.Chat(ctx)
if err != nil { log.Fatal(err) }

// Like ws.WriteMessage() — protobuf-encoded, type-checked at compile time
go func() {
    stream.Send(&pb.ChatMessage{Channel: "eng", Text: "hello"})
}()

// Like ws.onmessage — but invalid shapes never reach this line
for {
    msg, err := stream.Recv()
    if err == io.EOF { break }
    fmt.Println(msg.Channel, msg.Text)
}$escape$,
  $escape$go$escape$,
