INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'b2ad6bc6-07a9-4cbe-829b-7836fdb3cdb7',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$WebSockets and OpenAPI — Why You Need AsyncAPI Instead (and How to Generate Clients)$escape$,
  $escape$OpenAPI doesn't model WebSocket connections — it's built around request/response HTTP semantics. WebSockets are bidirectional, message-driven, and stateful, so the correct spec format is AsyncAPI 3.x. Think of it as OpenAPI's counterpart for event-driven protocols.

Spec-first: write your AsyncAPI YAML defining channels (`ws://api/feed`), message schemas (`BytePublished`, `CommentAdded`), and bindings (`ws` protocol). Then run `asyncapi generate` to scaffold typed server stubs and client SDKs. Your `onmessage` handlers get generated with discriminated-union message types — no hand-rolling switch statements.

Code-first: use libraries like `tsoa` (HTTP only) or manually annotate handlers, then emit the spec. For raw WebSocket servers in Node.js (`ws` library), there's no auto-spec generation — you own the YAML. This makes spec-first the stronger default: the spec is your contract, and `asyncapi validate` catches schema drift before `WebSocket.send()` ships malformed frames.

For documentation, `asyncapi/studio` renders interactive channel diagrams with full message payloads. Pair it with `@asyncapi/react-component` to embed living docs in your developer portal.$escape$,
  $escape$# Install AsyncAPI CLI
npm install -g @asyncapi/cli

# Validate your spec
asyncapi validate asyncapi.yaml

# Generate a TypeScript client
asyncapi generate fromTemplate asyncapi.yaml @asyncapi/ts-nats-template \
  --param server=production \
  -o ./generated/ws-client

# Generated client usage
import { ByteAIClient } from './generated/ws-client';
const client = new ByteAIClient();
client.subscribeToBytePublished((msg) => {
  console.log(msg.payload.byteId); // fully typed
});$escape$,
