INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'a9ad74e3-e6ec-4157-86c6-01d6c78a1071',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$WebSockets API Versioning — Subprotocol Negotiation vs URL Versioning$escape$,
  $escape$WebSocket versioning operates across two layers: the handshake and the message envelope. URL versioning (`wss://api.example.com/v2/events`) is blunt — the version is locked the moment the upgrade completes, and you're managing separate connection pools per version. The idiomatic alternative is subprotocol negotiation via `Sec-WebSocket-Protocol`: the client proposes an ordered list (`['app-v2', 'app-v1']`), the server selects the highest it supports, and echoes it in the `101 Switching Protocols` response. Read `socket.protocol` on the client to drive schema selection.

For backward compatibility, maintain a version-dispatch layer server-side. Route incoming frames to versioned handlers based on the negotiated subprotocol rather than branching inside shared logic. Stamp your JSON envelope with a `v` field (`{ "v": 2, "type": "tick", "data": {} }`) so a single server instance can handle mixed-version clients across concurrent long-lived connections.

The critical footgun: hard-closing connections when deprecating a version. Instead, push a `{ "type": "deprecation", "deadline": "2026-06-01", "migrate_to": "app-v3" }` frame over the old subprotocol, enforce a grace window, then remove the old subprotocol from your server's accepted list during the next deploy.$escape$,
  $escape$// Client: propose versions in preference order
const ws = new WebSocket('wss://api.example.com/events', ['app-v2', 'app-v1']);
console.log('Negotiated:', ws.protocol); // 'app-v2' or 'app-v1'

// Server (ws library): select highest mutual version
import { WebSocketServer } from 'ws';
const SUPPORTED = ['app-v2', 'app-v1'];

const wss = new WebSocketServer({
  handleProtocols: (protocols) =>
    SUPPORTED.find(v => protocols.has(v)) ?? false,
});

wss.on('connection', (socket) => {
  const handler = socket.protocol === 'app-v2' ? handleV2 : handleV1;
  socket.on('message', (raw) => handler(socket, JSON.parse(raw.toString())));
});$escape$,
  $escape$javascript$escape$,
