INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'cb0e11a5-cd56-48c7-8b31-62ffcbaa9c10',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$WebSockets Filtering — Query Params, Subscription Messages, and GraphQL Args$escape$,
  $escape$The browser WebSocket API offers no way to set custom headers during the handshake, so query parameters on the upgrade URL become your primary mechanism for initial filter state: `new WebSocket('wss://api.example.com/events?topic=payments&minAmount=500&sort=desc')`. Server-side, parse these in the HTTP upgrade handler before the connection is promoted — reject invalid filters with a `400` before the socket is ever opened.

For runtime re-filtering without reconnecting, define a typed control message: `{ type: 'subscribe', filter: { topic, minAmount }, sort: { field, dir } }`. The server updates the per-connection filter state and drains any buffered messages that no longer match.

With GraphQL subscriptions, the same logic moves into resolver args: `subscription { paymentStream(minAmount: 500, sort: DESC) { id, amount } }`. The resolver receives `args` at subscription setup time — validated once, applied on every publish.

For Protobuf over WebSockets, encode your filter as a `SubscribeRequest` message with dedicated scalar fields and an `enum SortDir` rather than freeform strings, giving you schema enforcement and compact framing on high-frequency streams.$escape$,
  $escape$// Attach initial filter via URL query params (browser WebSocket API)
const filter = new URLSearchParams({
  topic: 'payments',
  minAmount: '500',
  sort: 'desc',
});
const ws = new WebSocket(`wss://api.example.com/events?${filter}`);

// Runtime re-filter without reconnecting
ws.send(JSON.stringify({
  type: 'subscribe',
  filter: { topic: 'payments', minAmount: 1000 },
  sort: { field: 'createdAt', dir: 'desc' },
}));$escape$,
